Scripture:&nbsp;Luke 3: 21-22; 4:1-15 (Pastor Rose Bender)
From now through Easter&mdash;our theme is &ldquo;Moving towards Jesus as our center&rdquo; (key verse 1 Cor 3:11).&nbsp;
11&nbsp;For no one can lay any foundation other than the one already laid, which is Jesus Christ.
We will be using a study of the Gospel of Luke to do this and also some texts from the book of Hebrews.&nbsp; The Luke texts emphasize Jesus&rsquo; humanity.&nbsp; The Hebrews texts remind us of Jesus&rsquo; divinity.
&nbsp;

Scripture:&nbsp;Luke 3:7-18; Isaiah 12:2-6&nbsp;(Pastor Rose Bender)
Living out the song of salvation in the midst of darkness -- Prophet Isaiah does it and he invites us to sing this song of salvation even when we are in the middle of despair.&nbsp;
Zephaniah 3 gives us an image of God&nbsp;rejoicing over us with gladness;

Scripture:&nbsp;Malachi 3:1-4 (Pastor Rose Bender)
&ldquo;Flood of Mercy&rdquo; is our theme for Advent. The theme is about how God comforts and disturbs, two ideas that are hard to hold together. We know what it&rsquo;s like to be flooded with joy and excitement, overwhelmed by God&rsquo;s love. We also know that sometimes flood carry away and destroy things that matter. The image of a flood fits well with this season, which at the same time calls us to repentance and invites us into new life.&nbsp;
Malachi asks -- Who can endure&nbsp;the day of his coming?&nbsp;Who can stand&nbsp;when he appears? For he will be like a refiner&rsquo;s fire&nbsp;or a launderer&rsquo;s soap.&nbsp;He does not sugar coat what it means to be invited into new life but in His tender mercy God purifies us through the refiner's fire and destroys the impurities.

Scripture:&nbsp;Matthew 6:19-34; Luke 6:38 (Pastor Rose Bender) Our hard stewardship questions
How to prepare responsibly for retirement? How can we be accountable to each other with regard to finances? How do you pick and choose charities? If I give and am still able to make a savings, should I feel guilty? How much should I give? Is saving money for retirement/rainy day really biblical? Or is it just a part of our Swiss/German heritage?&nbsp; What about Jesus&rsquo; parable of the man who built &lsquo;bigger barns?&rsquo; How can we stop giving at 10% when there are so&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; many with so little? 40%? 80%? Are we instead responsible for stopping just short of being a burden on society? 10% before or after taxes? (could be a 30% difference) Can we talk about our choices of money? How do we&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; create space for honest conversation? Would be useful, humbling, maybe encouraging to hear what people do with what they have&hellip;would like to talk about mutual aid as well.
Giving&hellip;to whom? How much?
a. 10% of your net income to the church and any extra you have to charities of your choosing. b. Take care of all my bills and needs--then whatever I have left can go to the church. c. Give to whatever appeals to my sympathy/emotions at the time.
Not how much of&nbsp;my money&nbsp;will I give to God, but how much&nbsp;of God&rsquo;s money&nbsp;will I keep for myself? --John Wesley
Saving&hellip;how much? Planning for retirement?&nbsp;
a. Give 10%, save 10%, live off 80% b. Save, invest, and save some more.&nbsp; You have to be prepared. c. Instant gratification is the name of the game&mdash;you can&rsquo;t take it with you, so why save?
Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moths and vermin destroy, and where thieves break in and steal. But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven&hellip;. for where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.&nbsp;
Accountability&hellip;who do we talk to about how to spend our money?
a. My money, my businessb. If I start talking about it, people will judge me.&nbsp;c. That&rsquo;s what financial planners are paid to do.&bull; Do you accept the Word of God as guide and authority for your life?&bull; Are you willing to give and receive counsel in the congregation?&bull; Are you ready to participate in the mission of the church?&nbsp;

Scripture: 2 Corinthians 8: 1-15 (Pastor Rose Bender) Money is not mentioned in this scripture text, it talks about giving. Grace is mentioned 10 times. Verse 9 says ...so that you through his poverty might become rich. Why should we give?
&bull; Giving is a ministry that we have been given by God &bull; To keep our commitments &bull; Mutual care &bull; Gift of Jesus to us &bull; For the Glory of God &nbsp; How should we give?
&bull; Generously&mdash;out of our abundance &bull; Proportionally&mdash;according to what we have been given &bull; Sacrificially&mdash;beyond our own power &bull; Voluntarily &bull; Systematically &bull; Cheerfully/joyfully &nbsp;
